1st infraorbital is a flat bone with laminar posterior and median extensions
the posterior extension of the infraorbital is greatly reduced
the bone is largely reduced into a needle-like element lacking posterior and median extensions

bone is simple, flat and relatively large, and has its ventral articulatory head prominently protruding than its dorsal counterpart. The element is largely associated with labial tissue of the upper jaw.

the two articulatory heads of the maxillary are more developed and approximately equal in size. Proximally they form two delicate semi-circular structures which make it possible for the maxillary to turn 180Â· on the palatine. The distal portion of the maxillary is cylindrical rather than flat
the maxillary Is greatly reduced in size. The bone often terminates distally as a very thin plate
the metapterygold is a simple, evenly thin bony plate

the bone bears a dorsomedian lamina, on ventromedian surface of which a large portion of the adductor arcus palatini muscle inserts (The muscle normally Inserts on median margin of dorsal surface of the bone In other siluroids)

the metapterygoid becomes greatly thickened and trapezoidal. Quite often depth of the bone is much greater than the width. It appears such appearance of the bone is partially due to extendal growth of the dorsomedian lamina and partially due to twist of the metapterygold. Anteromedian end of the bone, where the ligament from the cranium attaches appears to have turned dorsally so that the attachment of the ligament Is dorsally shifted
the metapterygoid normally has its whole posterior edge contacting the quadrate and the hyomandlbular and forms a smooth anterior extension of the suspensorium
the metapterygoid, has long free posterior edge; in fact posterior margin of the bone Is very thin, too thin for any kind of connection
the bone has lost the contact with the hyomandibular but firmly sutured to the quadrate
Ithe direct contact with the quadrate Is also lost and only linked to it by a small piece of cartilage and ligamentous tissue
the posttemporal is normally a large triparte bone with a small inferior laminar extension. The bone usually has no contact with airbladder

the lamina is enlarged and is broadly in contact with the airbladder which in other siluroids is normally separated from the bone by the thick or broad Mullerian process. The disctinctively modified Miillerian process which is very thin contacts the posttemporal in a crescentic ring at posteromedian side of the lamina. The contact of these two elements is separatable as there is no suture or massive tissue involved. instead a long welldefined ligament, which is visible posteriorly, links the two elements

the posttemporal forms a large canal instead of a gutter-like trough to accommodate the peg of the cletthrurn. The canal appears to have developed from the gutter-like trough via ossification of the massive ligamentous tissue which spans at mouth of the gutter-like trough in other siluroids. The formation of the canal greatly increases the posterior surface of the posttemporal which broadly contacts the airbladder
a further modification has developed where the bone actually forms a deep smooth concavity in which a portion of the airbladder nests
the parapophysis of the complex vertebra produces anterolaterally into a prominent process, the Mullerian process. This process is normally thick and unflexible in most siluroids

the process becomes elongated and flexible, and is anteroventrally turned and curved. The process Is often anteroposterlorly compressed and bears an extension of elastic tissue which attaches on airbladder. Anteriorly the process is in close contact with the posttemporal along its length. An intermediate stage occures in the Mullerian process, though flexible, 15 comparatively more broader and thicker
an intermediate stage occures in the Mullerian process, it is very thin and with a long distal extension which is continued in a string of ligamentous tissue
plesiomorphic condition of the parapophysis of the complex vertebra appears to be where the parapophysis has two lateral processes at each side and a deep cleft between the two processes

the cleft between the processes is largely fulfllled by a thin laminar ossification. Lateral profile of the lamina gradually turns inwards towards the Mullerian process (anterior one of the two) and leaves a shallow concavity behind the Mullerian process

a laminar outgrowth on anterolateral margin is produced so that the lateral edge of the parapophysis is largely or completely in contact with body skin. The growth narrows or closes the shallow concavity and leaves a small notch or a hole on the margin near the Mullerian process

the anterolateral lamina joins base of the Mullerian process so that there is no notch along the lateral edge of the lamina. In these two genera the whole lateral edge is directly in touch with body skin along Its length. Presence of a small hole on the lamina behind the Mullerian process, demonstrates that such a modification has happened
the dorsal portion is normally short, triangular and posteriorly inmovably sutured to the nuchal plate
the dorsal portion of the interneural is greatly narrowed, often elongated and Is posteriorly movably connected to the nuchal plate via ligamentous tissue
a reduced interneural occurs as a very thin small piece
the dorsal portion of the interneural is absent
head is anteriorly rounded and depressed, and the mouth is terminal or subterminal
head is anterior produced into a prominent protruding snout which is apparantly deeper than that in the other taxa, and hence the mouth becomes ventrally situated (inferior mouth)
the snout is greatly deepened and Its depth is approximately equal or greater than Its width
